Bumi, Chandra Asri, Garuda Indonesia: Indonesia Equity Preview

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-06-22T01:47:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-22/bumi-chandra-asri-garuda-indonesia-indonesia-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
may have unusual moves in Indonesian trading. Stock symbols are
in parentheses, and share prices are as of the previous close.  The  Jakarta Composite index (JCI)  rose 1.8 percent to 3,794.94.  Metal producers: Tin for three-month delivery advanced 2.6
percent to $25,450 a metric ton in  London  yesterday and nickel
futures rose 1.1 percent to $21,880 a ton.  PT Timah (TINS IJ), Indonesia’s largest producer of tin,
climbed 1.1 percent to 2,400 rupiah and PT International Nickel
Indonesia (INCO IJ), the nation’s biggest producer of the metal,
was unchanged at 4,500 rupiah.  PT Bumi Resources (BUMI IJ): Indonesia’s biggest coal
producer and four of its units received $200 million of loans
from UBS AG to help fund expansion,  Bisnis Indonesia  reported,
citing Bumi’s first-quarter report and Director Dileep
Srivastava. The loans have a 6 percent interest rate per year,
the newspaper said. Bumi jumped 4.2 percent to 3,100 rupiah.  PT Chandra Asri Petrochemical (TPIA IJ): The company’s
shareholders approved a plan to set up a unit that will operate
a port in  Indonesia ’s Banten province to generate “recurring
income,” the polypropylene producer said in an e-mailed
statement. Chandra Asri climbed 0.6 percent to 4,025 rupiah.  PT Garuda Indonesia (GIAA IJ): Indonesia’s biggest airline
ordered 25 Airbus SAS A320s, including 10 A320neos, as it
replaces a fleet of Boeing Co. single-aisle aircraft at its low-
cost unit. The contract, worth about $2.2 billion at list
prices, also includes options for another 25 A320neo planes,
Garuda Chief Financial Officer Elisa Lumbantoruan said by e-
mail. Garuda was unchanged at 530 rupiah.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Berni Moestafa in Jakarta at 
 bmoestafa@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at   dboey@bloomberg.net  